Yes, hosting this on your existing Vultr instance is a perfect way to keep it running live 24/7. Since you already have a bot running there, you can leverage that same server to host this dashboard.

However, because your current frontend code relies on client-side browser requests to Yahoo Finance and Anthropic, **it will fail due to security blocks (CORS) and expose your private API keys.** To make it work 24/7 on Vultr, we need to structure it with a tiny backend proxy that fetches the data securely and serves the HTML page. Here is the easiest, most robust way to set it up.

---

## The Recommended Stack for Your Vultr Server

Instead of just hosting a raw HTML file, we will use **Node.js** with **Express**. The server will:

1. Securely hold your Anthropic API key.
2. Act as a proxy to fetch Yahoo Finance data (bypassing CORS).
3. Serve your updated frontend dashboard to the web.

### Step 1: Prepare the Files on Your Vultr Server

SSH into your Vultr instance, create a new directory, and initialize a Node project:

```bash
mkdir lunch-money-dashboard
cd lunch-money-dashboard
npm init -y
npm install express dotenv cors

```

### Step 2: Create the Backend Proxy (`server.js`)

Create a file named `server.js` in that folder. This backend handling prevents any API or CORS blocks:

```javascript
const express = require('express');
const cors = require('cors');
const path = require('path');
require('dotenv').config();

const app = express();
app.use(cors());
app.use(express.json());

// Serve static files (your HTML frontend)
app.use(express.static(path.join(__dirname, 'public')));

// PROXY 1: Yahoo Finance Data
app.get('/api/finance/:ticker', async (req, res) => {
    try {
        const ticker = encodeURIComponent(req.params.ticker);
        const url = `https://query1.finance.yahoo.com/v8/finance/chart/${ticker}?interval=1d&range=12d`;
        const response = await fetch(url);
        if (!response.ok) return res.status(response.status).json({ error: 'Failed to fetch Yahoo data' });
        const data = await response.json();
        res.json(data);
    } catch (err) {
        res.status(500).json({ error: err.message });
    }
});

// PROXY 2: Anthropic AI Assistant
app.post('/api/ai', async (req, res) => {
    try {
        const response = await fetch('https://api.anthropic.com/v1/messages', {
            method: 'POST',
            headers: {
                'Content-Type': 'application/json',
                'x-api-key': process.env.ANTHROPIC_API_KEY,
                'anthropic-version': '2023-06-01' // Standard header for Anthropic API
            },
            body: JSON.stringify({
                model: 'claude-3-5-sonnet-20241022', // Updated to stable 2026 production build
                max_tokens: 1000,
                messages: [{ role: 'user', content: req.body.prompt }]
            })
        });
        const data = await response.json();
        res.json(data);
    } catch (err) {
        res.status(500).json({ error: err.message });
    }
});

const PORT = process.env.PORT || 3000;
app.listen(PORT, () => console.log(`Lunch Money running live on port ${PORT}`));

```

### Step 3: Move and Update Your Frontend

Create a `public` folder inside your directory and save your HTML code inside it as `index.html`:

```bash
mkdir public
nano public/index.html

```

Inside your `index.html`, **update the network paths** so they talk to your new Vultr backend backend instead of hitting external APIs directly:

1. **Update `fetchQuote` URL to point to your proxy:**
